  "prompt": "What does \"net 30\" mean vs. \"due in 30 days\"?",
  "response": "\"Net 30\" and \"due in 30 days\" are terms used in invoicing and payment terms, but they can imply slightly different things depending on the context.\n\n1. **Net 30**: This term indicates that the full payment for the invoice is due within 30 days of the invoice date. It is a standard payment term used in business transactions, meaning that the buyer has 30 days to pay the total amount without incurring any late fees or penalties. If the invoice is issued on January 1, the payment should be made by January 31.\n\n2. **Due in 30 days**: This phrase also implies that payment is expected 30 days from the date of the invoice. It is essentially synonymous with \"Net 30.\" However, it may be used in a more general context and could potentially include different terms or stipulations depending on the agreement between the parties involved.\n\nIn summary, both terms generally mean that payment is expected within 30 days, but \"Net 30\" is a more formal term commonly found in invoicing.",
